Learning Objectives¶

By the end of this lecture, participants should understand:

  • What are basic data types and operations which can be performed on data
  • How to load data within a Pandas DataFrame
  • How to perform common data modifications
  • How Pandas as a framework helps in data analysis
  • How to visualise data with widely used modules

In [ ]:
import requests
import zipfile
import os
from io import BytesIO

# Meta, "Movement Range Maps" Humanitarian Data Exchange. (Part1 and Part2 of the Data)
zf2020 = zipfile.ZipFile(BytesIO(requests.get("https://data.humdata.org/dataset/c3429f0e-651b-4788-bb2f-4adbf222c90e/resource/3d77ce5c-ab6d-4864-b8a2-c8bafffac4f3/download/movement-range-data-2020-03-01-2020-12-31.zip").content)) if not os.path.exists("movement-range-data-2020-03-01-2020-12-31.zip") else zipfile.ZipFile("movement-range-data-2020-03-01-2020-12-31.zip")
mobilitydata1 = pd.read_csv(zf2020.open('movement-range-data-2020-03-01--2020-12-31.txt'), delimiter="\t", parse_dates=["ds"], low_memory=False)

zf2021 = zipfile.ZipFile(BytesIO(requests.get("https://data.humdata.org/dataset/c3429f0e-651b-4788-bb2f-4adbf222c90e/resource/55a51014-0d27-49ae-bf92-c82a570c2c6c/download/movement-range-data-2022-03-06.zip").content)) if not os.path.exists("movement-range-data-2022-03-06.zip") else zipfile.ZipFile("movement-range-data-2022-03-06.zip")
mobilitydata2 = pd.read_csv(zf2021.open('movement-range-2022-03-06.txt'), delimiter="\t", parse_dates=["ds"], low_memory=False)

Visualisation/Visualization¶

  1. Set the context
  2. Know your audience(s)
  3. Choose an effective visual
  4. Keep it simple (Ockham’s razor)

https://www.ibm.com/cloud/learn/data-visualization

https://journals.plos.org/ploscompbiol/article?id=10.1371/journal.pcbi.1003833

Visualisation/Visualization (Cont'd)¶

  1. Remember labels/legends/titles
  2. Use colours judiciously/appropriately
  3. Highlight the important parts (without being misleading)
  4. Every pixel matters
  5. Use standard methods, or create your own standard methods
  6. Use standard figure types for the message
